# Local Workflow Rules

## Handoff Startup
- Before processing any new handoff, `ready_for_next.sh` automatically syncs your worktree to trunk. Do not add per-role sync steps — the delivery script handles this.
- Before going idle on `NO_TASK`, check CI on your last handed-off commit (`gh pr checks` or `gh run list`); a red run on your own work is an implicit task.

## Swarmforge Feedback
- When ≥2 roles in the same pipeline run report the same failure mechanism (same failure class, similar root cause), the curator must surface this as a systemic gap in `.agents/backlog.md` regardless of whether individual items were `swarmforge`-scoped.

## QA Handoffs
- A QA handoff does not interrupt current work. If a QA wake-up arrives while working, ignore it and let `done_with_current.sh` deliver the next queued task or batch after the current work is complete.
- When a helper-delivered task is from QA, merge the sender commit identified by the printed `PAYLOAD` (`merge_and_process QA <commit>`). Every agent except the specifier must run unit tests and acceptance tests and fix any failures. Then run `done_with_current.sh`. Do not send a `git_handoff` downstream. Apart from merge, verification, and any QA-completion steps in your role prompt, do not apply other role-specific work to that QA handoff.
- **Exception — integrator:** a QA `git_handoff` to the integrator IS the final pipeline handoff; apply all role-specific integration steps (branch, PR, merge). "Do not send downstream" means do not re-forward to another pipeline role — it does not mean skip PR creation.
- **Exception — routed-back contradictions:** when QA's handoff routes a spec/design contradiction back upstream for resolution (not verification of your work), resolve it, commit, and send a `git_handoff` forward down the normal pipeline so QA re-verifies the resolution. The no-forward rule applies only to verification handoffs.
